| If I ever want to use something other than 0.13.2 debug registers, the
| following code can be put into a separate file, perhaps called
| debug-module.mu4. But for now I'm putting it here.

| In order to interact with the Debug Module on the target chip, we need
| some kind of transport. We assume here that such a transport - over JTAG,
| via a WCH Link device, etc - has been loaded and has defined two
| primitives for us: dm@ and dm! which read and write the debug module
| registers.

| XXX testing! This prints out the actions that would be taken.
: dm!  swap u. u. ." dm!  " ;
: dm@          u. ." dm@  " ;

: cmd!  700 abstractcs dm!  ( clear cmderr bits)  command dm! ;

| Bit definitions for the command register.
| "aar" stands for "abstract access register" - command 0.

| Sizes: 2 means 32 bits; 3 means 64 bits.
: >aarsize  #20 << ;

1 #19 << constant aarpostincrement
1 #18 << constant postexec
1 #17 << constant transfer
1 #16 << constant write       | XXX rename to not conflict with i/o write?

2 >aarsize  transfer +  constant transfer32

| The lowest bits of command are the "regno" field.
| 0000 - 0fff: CSR
| 1000 - 101f: GPR (the core integer registers)
| 1020 - 103f: floating point registers

| Read or write a CSR.
: csr@  ( csr# - val)                  [ transfer32         #] +  cmd!  data0 dm@ ;
: csr!  ( val csr#)    swap data0 dm!  [ transfer32 write + #] +  cmd! ;

| Read or write a core register.
: reg@  ( reg# - val)  1000 + csr@ ;
: reg!  ( val reg#)    1000 + csr! ;

| Once we have an easy way to compile instructions and put them into the
| progbuf, we can use lw and sw instructions to read and write memory.
|
| Since all the debug module registers - including the progbuf registers -
| live outside of the 32-bit address space, we start by creating a new
| aspace - a separate address space - to hold our instructions.
|
| There are at most 16 4-byte progbuf slots - 64 bytes - so we need
| log_2(64) or 6 bits of address space. Let's put that in our aspace and
| use 64 as the byte count for the memory image. And we will make a single
| *region* pointing into the image, called debug.

#16 \m cells      | space required for 16 progbuf instructions
dup log_2 drop    | bits required for our aspace
make-aspace  swap make-image  make-region debug

h @  ( save region)
debug  0 region!  zero-image    | clear it out

| Let's compile something!
__asm   0 x5 x6 lw  4 x5 c.addi  ;c
h !  ( restore region)

| We can also use assembler macros to do the same thing, so it's easy to
| compile code to read memory, write memory, jump off into the weeds, etc.

| Before copying the instructions in the debug region to the progbuf we
| want to add an ebreak at the end so the user doesn't have to.
|
| If the core has compressed instructions (C-ext is defined) then we can
| use c.ebreak instead of ebreak. We do this when we need to "pad" a
| progbuf slot that only contains a single compressed instruction. In this
| case, \m here - our pointer into the debug region - will be equal to 2
| modulo 4. Since we never add anything other than 2 or 4 to the dictionary
| pointer, we only have to check the state of the "2" bit.

: compile-ebreak
.ifdef C-ext   | if we have compressed instructions
   \m here  2 and if  \a c.ebreak  ^  then
.then
   \a ebreak ;

| Add an ebreak to the end of the instruction list in the debug region,
| copy the instructions to the progbuf registers, and then empty the debug
| region.

: progbuf!
   h preserve  debug  compile-ebreak
   region swap  do  i image-@  i \m cell/ progbuf0 + dm!  \m cell  +loop
   0 region! ( empty debug region) ;
